    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Shock Waves From the Mideast, on Two Fronts</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Amy Svirsky Abolafia letter says violence against Israel suggests Palestinians do not want peace and have not negotiated in good faith, since government looking for peace would be preparing its citizens for reality of compromise (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''2 Israeli Soldiers Slain by a Mob; Helicopters Hit Back'' (front page, Oct. 13):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''2 Israeli Soldiers Slain by a Mob; Helicopters Hit Back'' (front page, Oct. 13):</p>
        <p>If the Palestinians really want peace, why don't they practice nonviolence? It worked for India.</p>
        <p>The current violence suggests that the Palestinians do not want peace and that their negotiations have not been in good faith. A government that truly wants peace would prepare its citizens for the reality of peace by informing them of realistic expectations: they will not get everything they want, and Israel is not going away.</p>
        <p>AMY SVIRSKY ABOLAFIA  Delmar, N.Y., Oct. 13, 2000</p>
      </block>
